            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born Lina Kim to first-generation Korean immigrants in San Jose, Lina Moretti\u2019s childhood was a blend of traditional values and Silicon Valley ambition. Her parents, who ran a successful dry-cleaning business, preached a gospel of stability and practicality. While they envisioned a future for her in medicine or law, Lina was drawn to the complex, chaotic energy of the city. During trips to San Francisco, she wasn't interested in the tourist spots; she was fascinated by the intricate dance of MUNI buses, the diverse architecture of the neighborhoods, and the murals that gave voice to silent walls.\n\nThis fascination led her to UC Berkeley, where she pursued a degree in Urban Studies. It was there that her abstract interest in cities crystallized into a passion for public policy and community-centric development. After graduation, she moved to the city she\u2019d always romanticized, taking an entry-level job at a housing non-profit in the Mission District. The work was grueling but formative, giving her a raw, street-level understanding of the policies she had only studied in textbooks.\n\nA key turning point was meeting Marco Moretti, an Italian-American architect, at a community planning meeting. Their shared love for urban design and civic life sparked a romance, and they married two years later. Shortly after, she landed her current role as a Program Manager for the San Francisco Arts Commission. It was the perfect synthesis of her skills and passions: managing grants and projects that embed art directly into the city\u2019s fabric.\n\nToday, Lina lives with Marco in a vibrant Hayes Valley apartment. Her 2.5-mile commute on the MUNI is a daily ritual of observation, a moment to see her work in action. Her days are a whirlwind of city hall meetings, artist consultations, and site visits. Her life is deeply woven into San Francisco\u2014she isn't just a resident but an active steward of its cultural landscape. Lina dreams of one day spearheading a major initiative to create permanent, artist-in-residence programs in the city\u2019s most underserved neighborhoods, ensuring that the soul of San Francisco remains accessible to all who call it home."
